Sprint 51e: DRM flat operator precedence by default + Precedence: c pragma

The --parse-with-dylan byte-identical gate exposed that the Rust
front-end parser climbed C-style operator precedence, while real Dylan
(and the Dylan-in-Dylan parser) is flat left-associative: all binary
operators share one precedence, so `3 + 4 * 5` is `(3 + 4) * 5 = 35`,
not 23 (DRM rule). The Rust reference parser was silently mis-parsing
every mixed-operator expression.

Parser: collapse the six precedence-climbing functions into one flat
left-associative parse_binary (default). `:=` stays right-assoc/lowest;
unary stays tighter. A `Precedence:` module-header pragma selects the
mode: default flat (correct Dylan), `Precedence: c` opts a legacy file
into C-style climbing. Both modes retained behind the header.

Why a pragma: the entire hand-written corpus was authored assuming C
precedence -- pervasively, in boolean/comparison chains
(`b = 95 | b = 33`, `c >= 48 & c <= 57`) that flat-left silently
mis-groups, breaking the self-hosted lexer's character classification.
Rather than a risky big-bang rewrite, the pragma is a migration bridge:
default is correct-flat (real third-party Dylan parses right with no
annotation); legacy files grandfather in with one header line and get
parenthesized over time.

Grandfathered with `Precedence: c`: the self-hosting trio
(dylan-lexer/parser/lex-shim), IDE + collections fixtures, AND the
stdlib (stdlib.dylan + win32-constants.dylan). The stdlib was the
hidden keystone -- it merges into every compiled program, so its
flat-miscompiled char predicates crashed the shim even though simple
evals (which don't call them) passed.

Parenthesized instead (small, now flat-correct, keeps the translate
gate agreeing): point.dylan, richards-shape{,-open}.dylan. Updated
bare-eval value tests to flat results (1 + 2 * 3 = 9) and parenthesized
the inline-source closure/arity tests.

Green: value tests, macro_engine, c3_oracle, aot_dylan, lexer/parser
oracles, jit_cache, rope, ide, multifile, macros, translate gate,
coverage. nod-reader builds both modes; clippy clean.

Next: remove the translator's nested-binop fallback guard (both parsers
now flat for non-pragma files -> nested binops agree -> the blocked
files translate), migrate Precedence: c files to parens over time, and
teach the Dylan-in-Dylan parser the pragma.

